Male":"Deceased","1665–1729":"1665–1729","1667":"1667","1665":"1665","1741":"1741","9 Januar 1691":"9 January 1691","20 Juli 1729":"20 July 1729","1729":"1729","1705":"1705","23 December 1705":"23 December 1705","1746":"1746","Bierbach, Pfalz, Bayern, Deutschland":"Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany","Bierbach, Blieskastel, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany":"Bierbach, Blieskastel, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wagner","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) (also <b>Wägner</b>): occupational name for a carter and (in some dialects) a cartwright, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>wagen</i> ‘cart, wagon’, German <i>Wagen</i>. This surname is also established in many other parts of Europe, notably in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Britain, Poland, and Denmark. In Hungary it is mostly spelled <b>Wágner</b> and <b>Vágner</b>. In Russia, Czechia, Croatia, Slovenia, and Slovakia it is also found in the Slavicized form   Vagner  . Compare   Wagener  ,   Waggener  , and   Wagoner  .","Dutch and perhaps also English: occupational name from Middle Dutch <i>waghenaer</i> ‘carter’ (compare 1 above). The Dutch word is not known to have been borrowed into English before 1600 but the surname <i>Wagner</i> is recorded in Norfolk (England) from 1379, perhaps a substitution of the Dutch word for Middle English <i>wainer</i>. Compare   Waggoner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Waggener","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Wagner   or its variant   Wagener  . Compare   Waggoner  ."]},{"name":"Wagler","meanings":["German: variant of   Wagner  ."]},{"name":"Wanger","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Franz, Aloysius, Frieda, Heinz, Kurt, Manfred.","German:","habitational name for someone from any of various places called Wang (Bavaria, Austria) or Wangen."]},{"name":"Waggoner","meanings":["Americanized form of German or Dutch   Wagner   or its German and Dutch variants   Wagener   and   Wagenaar  . Compare   Waggener   and   Wagoner  .","Possibly also English: altered form of   Waghorn  . The surname <i>Waggoner</i> is very rare in Britain.","History: A planter named John Waggener or Waggoner, who came to America <i>c.</i> 1670 and lived in Essex County, VA, is said to have been born in Colchester, Essex (England). No documentary source for this origin is given and an English origin is difficult to establish. The nearest similar English surname is   Wagner   2, a very rare Norfolk name, originating in the 14th-century. In 17th-century Kent a number of families named <i>Waghorn</i> alias <i>Wagon</i> were occasionally also known as <i>Waggoner</i> (through false association with that word). Direct derivation from the English word <i>wag(g)on</i> is not possible, since it was borrowed into English only in the 16th century from Dutch, and <i>wag(g)oner</i> is an early Modern English coinage."]},{"name":"Waner","meanings":["Swabian habitational name for someone from a place called Wain, or from Wahn near Cologne.","possibly an altered form of <b>Wähner</b>, a variant of   Wagner  .","German (<b>Wäner</b>):"]},{"name":"Vagner","meanings":["Jewish (Ashkenazic), Czech, Slovenian, and Croatian; Hungarian (<b>Vágner</b>); Slovak (also <b>Vágner</b>): occupational name for a carter or cartwright, of German origin (see   Wagner  ), often applied as a translation into German of corresponding Slavic occupational names or surnames."]},{"name":"Wegner","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Dieter, Erwin, Gerhard, Heinz, Helmuth, Bernhard, Ernst, Hans, Alfons, Eldor.","German: northern and central variant of   Wagner  ."]},{"name":"Wagoner","meanings":["Americanized form of German or Dutch   Wagner   or its German and Dutch variants   Wagener   and   Wagenaar  . Compare   Waggoner  .","Possibly also English: variant of   Waggoner  . The surname <i>Wagoner</i> is very rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Wagener","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Fritz, Arno, Bernhard, Dieter, Horst, Johann, Klaus, Kurt, Matthias, Willi.","German: variant of   Wagner  ."]},{"name":"Wegener","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerhard, Heinz, Friedrich, Johannes, Lorenz, Armin, Eldor, Erna, Guenther, Hans, Kurt, Manfred.","German, Dutch, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Wagner  ."]}]},{"name":"Johann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Vernacular form of   Johannes ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Adam</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Johann Adam Wagner was born in 1665, in Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany. He married Anna Margaretha Kim on 9 January 1691, in Palatinate, Bavaria, Germany. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 4 daughters. He died on 20 July 1729, in his hometown, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1665–20 Juli 1729":"1665–20. juuli 1729","1667–1741":"1667–1741","1705–1746":"1705–1746","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1665–1729":"1665–1729","1667":"1667","1665":"1665","1741":"1741","9 Januar 1691":"9. jaanuar 1691","20 Juli 1729":"20. juuli 1729","1729":"1729","1705":"1705","23 December 1705":"23. detsember 1705","1746":"1746","Bierbach, Pfalz, Bayern, Deutschland":"Pfalz, Bayern, Saksamaa","Bierbach, Blieskastel, Saar-Pfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Germany":"Bierbach, Blieskastel, Saarpfalz-Kreis, Saarland, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"1665–20 Juli 1729":"1665–20. heinäkuuta 1729","1667–1741":"1667–1741","1705–1746":"1705–1746","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1665–1729":"1665–1729","1667":"1667","1665":"1665","1741":"1741","